9 September 2020

Recently finished full code for a hierarchical factor analysis using habitats first and SDM suitability second. Pixels without habitat data are classified using neighboring pixels if their centroids are on the mainland and they have a classified neighbour. Leftover pixels (usually islands) get their own habitat group. Each habitat gets a unique number of SDM-based subfactors. The number for each habitat is chosen based on variance explained (stop when adding a factor explains less than 1% more variance). Any pixels unclassified at the second level are again classified based on immediate neighbours, if possible. If not possible, they are left unclassified.

Produced a full typology using 9 habitats (+ islands/coast as a 10th), with a total of 50 units. Each of the top-level units also had a number of members that couldn't be classified with SDM-based factors (a total of 1884 pixels). 

I have thus far received very little feedback about the exploratory factor analyses I placed in oneDrive directly after the meeting. However, the current code can be easily modified to accommodate eventual decisions brought by the group. 


24 September 2020

On Aleks's suggestion, recently completed a dual factor analysis code that creates separate analyses for environmental data and SDM suitability data, and uses the intersection of the two for a candidate typology.  The hierarchical and dual factor analyses are identical on the first level, but some statistical tests confirm that there are significant similarities in the SDM-based classification when it is done within habitat units and for the whole continent at once. This is not surprising. Some visual checks, however, do show that very few units in the hierarchical analysis are more than 60% aligned with a unit in the dual analysis. 

The two candidate typologies seem to partially agree on areas with more or less spatial heterogeneity, though the dual analysis tends to have a bit less heterogeneity than the hierarchical analysis in any given locality, although not always. The dual factor analysis also has more units than the hierarchical analysis. 

I've fixed both analyses to be run on transformed data that more closely approximates normal distributions, removed distances (dist to coast, dist to geothermal), and fixed the nearest-neighbor analyses to work on all pixels such that only truly coastal pixels end up in the "islands" category. 

I'm beginning to work on a manuscript presenting the typology, thinking about how to frame such a paper.


9 Oct 2020

I've greatly abstracted, cleaned, and simplified the factor analysis code. It now performs hierarchical (environmental then sdm), dual (environmental and sdm for entire continent) and reverse hierarchical (sdm then environmental) factor analyses. 

A cursory analysis suggests reassuring amount of agreement between the two hierarchical approaches.
The dual analysis may show slightly better agreement with the reverse hierarchical approach (sdm factors first).


12 Nov 2020
First attempt at candidate typology "validation" is to see which typology (hierarchical, dual, or reverse hierarchical) aligns with greatest turnover between candidate units in point occurrences of species that were not used in the classification process (no SDM). So far, all measures point to the hierarchical candidate typology as providing the most turnover, though turnover is generally pretty low (similarity is high) among the candidate units. Reverse hierarchical approach is second best and the dual approach is worst. However, the difference between them is pretty small, a few percentage points at best. 

19 Nov 2020

Further rudimentary ecosystem validation shows the dual typology may be the best candidate.  It performs better (showing lower similarity between units) when the richness of units and their overlap is taken into account (simpairs null model) and also when correlations on the relative abundance of species in each unit is considered. Simple beta-diversity metrics are likely skewed here because of large discrepancies in the occupancy of ecosystem units (some contain hundreds of species, other only a handful). Possible zero-inflated poisson model to check coefficient estimates between ecosystem units???


14 Dec 2020

Met with Aleks and David.  We decided to stick with the hierarchical factor analysis. Time now to pivot toward individual ecosystem unit draft descriptions. I will start an R markdown doc which will have maps and descriptions of each ecosystem. Some points fromt the meeting: 
1. We will consider further splitting any ecosystems that occur in disparate locations across the continent.
2. Need to pick out most distinctive or common biotia and environmental factors for each unit in a standardised way. 
3. Begin compiling literature for each unit or group of units. 


10 May 2021

Profiles of ecosystem units have been completed in the interim. Workshop with small group of experts has been held in Hobart, with very positive feedback (at end of March 2021). Profiles were produced in word doc format and shortened/simplified for broader dissemination. New profiles included expanded descriptions and photos of ecosystem units where possible. Extensive maps were included as well, including summary maps of environmental groups and maps of individual units.

A manuscript describing the typology has been drafted and shared with Aleks and David. They will likely need to add citations and write a few paragraphs.

While in Hobart we met with Jonny Stark who gave us some good leads on data types needed for the nearshore typology. These need to be followed up with experts and data curators. 

A regional version of the terrestrial ice-free typology is underway, with units being split by ACBR, then subjected to a potential merging scheme that unifies ecosystems that are similar and broadly adjacent/contiguous (e.g. same ecosystem type in two neighbouring ACBRs). Possibility of discarding very small ecosystems that cannot be merged (largest is 40 pixels, likely 15-20km2 max). Regional-scale units will likely end up being the units that are risk-assessed under the IUCN RLE.


