12 August 2021

Following discussions with Aleks and Ben Raymond at the AAD data centre, we decided to rerun the classification using new higher-resolution versions of the initial abiotic data inputs. New layers were provided by Ben.

This is partially in response to comments from the group pointing out that the difference between env1 and env6 was dodgy because it was based on missing data. The new higher resolution data layers will allow us to formally classify pixels formerly in Env6. 

Additionally, I decided to pare down the number of variables included, removing sumptemp, ModisTemp, and DDminus5 as these are all correlated with meanTemp and did not add much to the classification judging by previous results. ModT also could not be extracted for edge pixels and DDminus5 had a highly skewed distribution not easily normalisable by conventional means. Though available, we also did not use aspect, which is a direct input of the calcualtion for the solar radiation layer. The fresh classification was thus run with 9 variables: c("cloud", "wind", "meanTemp", "melt","elevation", "rugosity", "slope", "totPrecip", "solar") 

Using the same procedure as previously described, I ran the hierarchical factor analysis (i.e., with minimum loading of 0.3 at the top level and minimum loading of 0.35 at the bottom level). The top level classification yielded 5 environments, and the second level yielded 5, 5, 6, 6, and 6 units for each environment, respectively. Next step is to undertake a comparison of the typologies to see which previous units have direct analogues in the new typology.


23 August 2021
The last attempt at the typology yielded ok results but the poor resolution of the SMD layers made the ecosystem units awkward and chunky. I produced 100m resolution versions of the SDM layers using cubic interpolation. Visual check confirms the results seem reasonable, without any outliers. 

I reran the typology with these smoother SDM layers, which should give more realistic results esp. when large unbroken areas of habitat exist, such as in the dry valleys. The top level classification yielded 5 environments, and the second level yielded 5, 5, 7, 6, and 5 units for each environment, respectively.

This new classification will be used to produce V5 of the typology and compare with V3 as described above.


20 September 2021
As of today the updated (V5) 100m resolution typology has been completed and described unit-by-unit. Text from the descriptions of V3 has been recycled where strong overlap between units was found, however, the improved resolution of the typology has ensured that most pixels of the previous typology are broken into 2 or more ecosystems in the new typology. The overview document and the reports have been updated to describe each unit based on 50% confidence ellipses around pairs of related variables (slope-elevation, melt-precip etc.). I have also found satellite images of nearly every ecosystem using Google Earth Pro. Because of the good resolution, it is clear from satellite photos where the ecosystem delineations are in most cases and it's often possible to tell how they relate to one another (e.g. sunny and shadowed slopes on the same nunatak). Also, I made a glossary of terms which should help clarify and standardise the language used to describe units across the entire typology. I made an effort to improve grammar, capitalisation, etc. throughout the unit descriptions, though another check through would probably be prudent.


There are some comments that came up in the elicitation process which have not been addressed properly yet:

1. Inclusion of additional variables: Geology, wind direction, topographic positioning index, albedo, and data on prokaryotes/soil microbiomes have all been brought up. Likely it is not actually feasible to include these.

2. Lakes and geothermal areas have not been superimposed.

3. Need to bring in and cite existing literature wherever possible. This represents likely quite a lot of work, and it's not necessarily obvious which papers would pertain to which units. However, there is probably some value to at least attempting some match-ups. 

